{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The type III secretion system of Gram-negative bacteria is used to transport virulence factors from the pathogen directly into the host cell [[cite:PUB00003585]] and is only triggered when the bacterium comes into close contact with the host. Effector proteins secreted by the type III system do not possess a secretion signal, and are considered unique because of this. Yersinia spp. secrete an effector protein called YopE through the type III needle [[cite:PUB00006632]]. This acts as a Rho GTPase-activating protein that disrupts the host cell actin cytoskeleton, and is regulated by a chaperone protein called SycE/YerA [[cite:PUB00007794]]. In the absence of the SycE chaperone, YopE is not transported through the needle and remains in the bacterial cytoplasm, so suggesting a crucial role for this moiety [[cite:PUB00006679]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "1l2w", "name" "Crystal Structure of the Yersinia Virulence Effector YopE Chaperone-binding Domain in Complex with its Secretion Chaperone, SycE"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pirsf" {"PIRSF011271" "Type III secretion system molecular chaperone protein SycE"}, "prints" {"PR01596" "SYCECHAPRONE"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Type III secretion chaperone SycE", "short" "T3SS_chp_SycE"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 7, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 9, "taxa" 140, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 327, "sets" 0, "proteins" 105, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 84}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR005416", :literature {"PUB00003585" {"URL" nil, "issue" "2", "authors" ["Hueck CJ."], "ISO_journal" "Microbiol. Mol. Biol. Rev.", "DOI_URL" "http://ukpmc.ac.uk/articlerender.cgi?tool=EBI&pubmedid=9618447", "medline_journal" "Microbiol Mol Biol Rev", "title" "